korean:
  title: 도 황제께 문안하는 글
  author: 이규보
  language: kor
  text: 기봉(箕封)에 몸이 매어 멀리 해뜨는 나라에 살면서, 한궐(漢闕)에 마음이 달려[懸] 멀리 하늘처럼 긴 성수(聖壽)를 축원하나이다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0420_010_0360&viewSync=OT
english:
  title: Memorial Presenting Salutations to the Emperor of the Upper Capital
  author: Lee Gyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Though my form remains bound within these eastern lands, far where the sun rises anew,
    My heart hangs ever toward the imperial halls,
    And from this distance, I offer prayers for the Emperor's years—
    As long and boundless as heaven itself.
  footnotes:
    - The 'eastern lands' refers to Korea, positioned east of the Yuan capital. 'Upper Capital' (上都) refers to Khanbaliq, the summer capital of the Yuan Dynasty.
    - The poem employs the classical conceit of physical distance from the center of power contrasted with unwavering spiritual devotion—a common trope in tributary poetry of the Goryeo period.
